  - Cards and panels should follow the specified shadow, border, and hover states.
- Performance:
  - Lazy load optional detailed content; avoid rendering heavy artifacts until requested.
  - Debounce expensive operations if they’re triggered by frequent state updates.
- Testing:
  - Unit tests for guard conditions: ensure (items ?? []).map(...) returns [] when items is null/undefined.
  - Smoke tests for loading, success, and failure render paths.
  - API-shape tests: ensure const result = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].

### Backend
- No external APIs required for this feature, but ensure endpoints that would feed loading/success/failure states return stable shapes:
  - Loading state: { status: "loading" } or through a streaming progress endpoint if implemented.
  - Success state: { status: "success", artifactUrls?: string[], nextSteps?: { title, href }[] }
  - Failure state: { status: "failure", errorCode: string, message: string, details?: string }
- Data validation:
  - Validate API responses to ensure response.data, response.error, etc., conform to expected shapes; provide safe defaults.

### Integration
- Flow:
  - A page or module action triggers an operation; display LoadingSpinner with status="loading".
  - On success, render StatusBanner variant="success" with title and optional NextStepsPanel.
  - On failure, render StatusBanner variant="failure" with ErrorSnippet and a Retry button (retryHandler).
- Data handling:
  - All arrays derived from API results should be guarded: (response?.data ?? []) and casted with Array.isArray checks when iterating.
  - Use Optional chaining for nested properties from API responses.
- Logging & telemetry:
  - When a run completes (success or failure), emit a structured log entry with runId, timestamp, status, and errorCode if applicable.
  - Include run artifacts references in the success payload when available.

## User Experience Flow
- Step 1: User initiates an operation (e.g., “Start data sync,” “Publish content,” “Run cronjob”).
- Step 2: UI shows a LoadingSpinner with a short, descriptive label (e.g., “Syncing data…”) and optional subtext.
- Step 3: Operation completes successfully.
  - UI transitions to a Success Banner with a strong title (e.g., “Data sync complete”).
  - Display optional next steps (e.g., “View artifacts,” “Schedule next run”) via NextStepsPanel.
- Step 4: Operation fails.
  - UI transitions to a Failure state with ErrorSnippet showing an errorCode and message.
  - Present Retry controls; provide an option to view logs or details in an expandable panel.
- Step 5: User interacts with next steps or retries; the system logs actions for auditing and traceability.

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models:
  - LoadingProgress: { id: string, status: 'loading'|'success'|'failure', message?: string, timestamp: string, runId?: string, artifacts?: string[] }
  - NextStep: { title: string, description?: string, href?: string }
  - ErrorInfo: { errorCode: string, message: string, details?: string }

- API Endpoints (examples; adapt to existing routing system):
  - GET /api/operations/:id/progress -> { status, message, runId, details? }
  - POST /api/operations/:id/retry -> { status, runId }
  - GET /api/operations/:id/artifacts -> { artifacts: string[] } (optional)
  - POST /api/operations/:id/abort -> { status }
- Security:
  - Ensure endpoints require proper authentication tokens/permissions.
  - Ensure any client-side interactions that trigger retries or next steps enforce user permissions.
- Validation:
  - Validate inputs for retry or next steps; reject if missing required fields.
  - Use null-safe patterns in all responses, e.g., response?.data, response?.error.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Loading state renders with an accessible spinner and descriptive text; no runtime errors if data is null or undefined.
- [ ] Success state renders a prominent banner with a valid title, optional subtext, and up to N next steps; next steps are navigable links.
- [ ] Failure state renders an error snippet with a structured errorCode and message, plus a functional Retry button that triggers a retry handler.
- [ ] All arrays and API results are guarded to avoid null/undefined dereferencing using data ?? [] and Array.isArray checks.
- [ ] useState hooks for all arrays/objects initialized with proper defaults (e.g., useState<Step[]>([]) or useState<string>("")).
- [ ] All API response shapes are validated before rendering; fall back to safe defaults when necessary.
- [ ] UI adheres to the project’s Visual Style and Typography guidelines, including color palette and spacing.
- [ ] Comprehensive unit tests cover loading, success, and failure rendering paths, plus guard conditions for array operations.

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Dark, modern UI with high contrast on primary text.
- Consistent elevation, borders, and subtle shadows across cards and panels.
- Use the Accent color sparingly for active indicators, errors, and CTAs.
- Maintain 8px baseline grid with 16/24/32 spacing multiples.
- Ensure left navigation and top navigation remain accessible and visually coherent with the Loading / Success pages.

## Visual Style

### Color Palette
- Primary background: #0B0B0C
- Secondary surface: #151718
- Tertiary surface / panel outline: #1F1F20
- Primary text / headings: #FFFFFF
- Secondary text / meta: #9DA3A6
- Subtle text / disabled: #56595B
- Accent (action / alert): #FF3B30
- Neutral highlight / icon fill: #CFCFCF
- Soft highlight / gloss: #E6E7E8
- Chart/status accents: teal #00C2A8, amber #FFB020, purple #8B5CF6
- Borders / dividers: rgba(255,255,255,0.03)
- Gradients: subtle gradient #111213 → #1A1A1B

### Typography & Layout
- Font family: Inter (or SF Pro Display / Roboto fallback)
- Weights:
  - Headings: 600–700, 20–28px
  - Card titles: 500–600, 14–16px
  - Body: 400, 12–14px
  - Microcopy: 300–400, 11–12px
- Spacing: 8px baseline; gutters 220–260px for sidebar; header 56–64px; card padding 16–20px
- Alignment: left-aligned lists in sidebar; main grid layout can be mixed but grid should feel balanced and dense for power users

### Key Design Elements
- Card Design: dark elevated cards, 8–12px radius, gradient fill, subtle borders and soft shadows; hover lifts and border tinting
- Navigation: left vertical nav with expandable sections; active state uses accent pill and subtle tint
- Data Visualization: minimal, muted gridlines, bold data lines with rounded caps; tooltips with white text on dark panels
- Interactive Elements: primary/secondary buttons, dark inputs with inner glow, labeled placeholders; micro-interactions with 120–200ms transitions
- Design Philosophy: focused, high-contrast, visually steady; support for fast scanning and auditability; clear, reversible actions

---

Connected Features:
- Error Handling & Validation: Consistent error patterns, client/server validation, user-friendly messages, and structured error codes for APIs.

